<content><section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001"><title>Learning Objectives</title>
  <para id="para-00001">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
 <list id="list-00001">
<item>State the four basic forces.</item>
<item>Explain the Feynman diagram for the exchange of a virtual photon between two positive charges.</item>
<item>Define QED.</item>
<item>Describe the Feynman diagram for the exchange of a   between a proton and a neutron.</item>
</list>
  </section>
    <para id="import-auto-id1169737814519">As first discussed in <link document="m42076">Problem-Solving Strategies</link> and mentioned at various points in the text since then, there are only four distinct basic forces in all of nature. This is a remarkably small number considering the myriad phenomena they explain. Particle physics is intimately tied to these four forces. Certain fundamental particles, called carrier particles, carry these forces, and all particles can be classified according to which of the four forces they feel. The table given below summarizes important characteristics of the four basic forces.</para><table id="import-auto-id1169738010507" summary="Properties of the Four Basic Forces"><title>Properties of the Four Basic Forces</title>
